{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696386/1930092001/0279.xml":{"full_text":"Further Attacks By Bears Upon Stock Market Is Predicted By Spectator\nDEVELOPMENT\nII RUBBER STRENGTH\nPrice Stabilization of Wheat Will Aid Re\ncovery of Stocks; Eastman Kodak at\nLevels Where Big Buys Were Made\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe wait-and-see advice I have been giving my readers for\nthe past week was justified yesterday when stock prices\ncrumbled all along the line. The break was the most drastic\nwe have had in over a month, and the good stocks went\ndown with the bad.\nThe bears are being successful in getting some liquidation,\nas yesterday\u2019s volume of about 3,000,000 shares proves. The\nreaction gives indications cf going farther.\nThere is a good deal of selling coming from those who are\ndisappointed with the extent of the business recovery. Stand\naside and let the storm blow over.\nMcKeesport\nThere are a number of indi\nvidual stocks that have been\npretty cheap right along and are\ngetting cheaper. McKeesport Tin\nPlate is one. It is selling under\n02, paying $5 and earning about\n$lO. General Refractories is an\nother, selling under 75 and earn\ning about $lO. Drug is a third.\nThis stock has a high investment\nrating and -is being steadily ac\ncumulated by far-sighted in\nvestors. j\nRubber Stocks\nStrength in the rubber stocks\nwas a surprising development.\nSettlement of the tire price war\nhelped. I hear of smart buying\nin Goodrich. Goodyear is a\nsplendid company, but hasn\u2019t\nbeen making money. It would be\nwell to stay away from this stock\nuntil the dividend status has\nbeen settled.\nI like Penick and Ford on any\nfurther reaction from these\nlevels. Warner Brothers is act\ning well considering the general\nstate of the market. The market\nis going to continue sour until\nwheat shows some signs of price\nStabilization.\nEastman Kodak is around the\nlevels at which insiders began\npicking up the stock In the June\n\"and August breaks. Eastman will\nbe a good buy under 200. Loril\nlard is another that is acting\nwell.\n\u201cTearing \u2019Em Down\u201d\nThe old bear crowd is at it\nagain, I am told. A house which\nhas acted for Livermore in the\npast was said to have been sell\ning stocks heavily yesterday.\nDanforth, the Boston bear, was\nlisted as operating on the short\nside in a big way, and also sev\neral others who have been in the\nlimelight since the bear market\nstarted in November. They are\nbeing followed by other bears, both\nbig and little, professional and\nnovice. At that I hear the short\ninterest in the market isn\u2019t as\nbig as the decline in prices would\nseem to indicate, for considerable\ncovering has been going on dur\ning the selling.\nThe smart bears never wait for\nbottom. They take their profits\nwhen stocks look their worst. It\u2019s\nthe amateur who is usually caught\nwaiting for the last eighth of a\npoint and gets his fingers burned.\nConsolidated Gas was like a\nthatch of fiery red hair in an\nAfrican jungle yesterday, closing\noff only .a fraction while other\nstocks were as many points lower\nand heading stubbornly through\nout the selling. A floor trader\nFreight Traffic In\nJuly Declines\nThe volume of freight traffic\nhandled by the Class I railroads\nof this country in July this year\namounted to 35,579,981,000 net\nton miles, according to reports\njust received from the railroads\nby the bureau of railway eco\nnomics and made public today.\nCompared with July, 1929, this\nwas a reduction of 6,429,418,000\nnet ton miles, or 15.3 per cent,\nand a reduction of 3,572,947,000\nnet ton miles, or 9.1 per cent,\nunder July, 1928.\nLead Production Up\n1,832 Tons in Aug.\nRefined lead production in the\nUnited States in August totaled\n58,036 short tons, against 56,204\ntons in July, an increase of 1,-\n832 tons. In June this year, out\nput amounted to 55.686 tons, ac\ncording to the American Bureau\nof Metal Statistics.\ny Stocks of refined copper at the\nend of August amounted to 72,832\ntons, against 62,880 tons at the\nend of July and 55,501 at the\nend of June.\n$711,000 RAIL BONDS\nThe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission authorized the Cleveland\nend Pittsburgh Railroad to issue\n$711,000 of refunding mortgage\n4*4 per cent gold bonds.\nTROUSERS\nTo Match Your Odd Coats\nEISEMAN\u2019S, 7th F\nWASHINGTON \"TBHiMHiGIAL NEWS\ntold me Gas was well bought all\nday. There are rumors of Elec\ntric Bond and Share buying. Gas\nis still\u2019the same old investment\nfavorite of a great many despite\nthe rate hearing mixup, but I\nwouldn\u2019t advise touching it at\nCurrent levels- while the stock list\nis under pressure.\n\u201cThe Buying\u201d\nWho\u2019s buying stocks, becomes\nthe question when prices seem to\nbe melting away, and even the\nhighest grade issues look like a\nplugged nickel. Yesterday the buy\ning came from many sources. The\nbears were there for one, taking\ntheir profits.\nThere was some investment\nbuying, not enough to turn the\ntide, but enough to give some\nsupport. This was centered in\nthe best stocks as Steel, Can, the\nAmerican Tobacco issues. General\nMotors, Telephone, and\nOne substantial order took a lot\nof Continental Can out of the\nmarket. A surprising develop\nment was public participation,\none of the Biggest houses in the\nStreet reporting heavy outside\nbuying.\nOne sign that the reaction is\nlikely to go further was given by\none of the members of the Ex\nchange, who said he saw no evi\ndence of aggressive support by\nthe so-called constructive forces.\nIn fact, one of the bull leaders\nsold a considerable amount of\nSteel.\nSponsors of quite a lew of the\nleaders, especially General Motors,\nSteel and Union Carbide, sold\nstock last week. They are said\nto be replacing their lines on a\nscale down.\n\u201cNear Bottom\u201d\nIt was noticeable that several\ngroups of stocks head strongly\nwhile prices of others were crack\ning. The coppers closed practical\nly unchanged. Despite all the bad\nnews about the red metal situa\ntion. price cuts, heavy surplus\nstocks and the like, strength in\nthis group would bear out the\nbelief that the coppers were\npretty thoroughly deflated.\nThe oils act as though they\nwere around bottom, too. The to\nbaccos and film stocks gave way\nmore than the above two, but\ntheir losses weren\u2019t extehsive, and\nthey show a big clearance from\ntheir low prices of the year. The\nrails also are acting well. Strength\nin these groups reveals good buy\ning and little if liny urgent sell\ning, and would indicate the like\nlihood they would be the first\nto turn when the market\nstrengthens.\nMissouri Pacific\nx To Enlarge Lines\nThe New Orleans. Texas and\nMexico Railroad asked authority\nof the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission to acquire control of the\n25-mile Rio Grande ,and Eagle\nPass road in Webb county, Texas.\nThe proposal calls for the pay\nment of $337,500 for the. road\u2019s\n6,000 shares of capital stock.\nThe former road is a part of the\nMissouri Pacific system.\nSIOO,OOO RAIL STOCK\nThe Fairport, Painesville and\nEastern Railroad asked the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission for\nauthority to issue SIOO,OOO of com\nmon stock. It will be offered to\nstockholders at par.\nChinese-American Restaurant Ama]\n14th and New York Ave.\nyj Now Open X\nafter complete redeenretfon. Some- L\nthing new\u2014something you'll like. f 'Vi\nDuring Lunch, Dinner A \\l\nDanCing and Supper j.\nV No cover Charge At Any Time\nDine!\u2014Dance! in This Gorgeous\nOriental Garden\nYl tW t\u00b0 he Heely music of\nalsakol Lotus Orchestra\nTH E V \u00bbV I \u2019!\u00ab.T'ON TIM ES\nj Recovery\nr W\ntiffin\n\u2014Time* Staff Photo\nG. L. BRYSON\nDISTRICT passenger agent\nfor the Canadian National Rail\nways here, who predicted a\ngradual return of prosperity.\nHe declared that reports just\nreceived show an increase in\nrailroad business,\nRECOVERY SEEN\nDY BRYSON\nRailroad business, both freight\nand passenger, is increasing. This\nis the conclusion drawn from\nlatest reports by G. L. Bryson,\nDistrict passenger agent of the\nCanadian National Railways here.\nHe said:\n\u201cIt is felt that undoubtedly\nthe peak of the business de\npression has been passed, and\nwe are looking forward to a\ngradual increase in revenue\neach month.\u201d\nBryson added that the con\nfidence his company had placed\nin the recovery has caused them\nto arrange that their Halifax-\nWest Indies ser\nvice steamers call at Boston on\nall trips. This is the first time\nthat Canadian National steamers\nhave called at an American port.\nRailroad Shares\nReports Increase\nNEW YORK. Sept. 20. \u2014Rail\nroad Shares Corporation report\nfor the period from July 3, 1929,\nto September 6, 1930, disclosed a\ngain in profits amounting to $462.\n491.\nSurplus and reserves as of Sep\ntember 6, totaled $237,480, of\nwhich $106,250. is required for\ndividends.\nWall Street\nHears:\nThat American Chicle will\nshow record earnings this year.\nThat copper companies will\ncut their dividends still fur\nther.\nThat Bangor Aroostook R.\nR. (BNK) is an attractive pur\nchase.\nThat many large concerns\nhave began placing orders for\ntheir future requirements and\nhave abandoned the hand-to\nmouth buying policy in the be\nlief that bottom prices have\nbeen reached.\nThat L. A. Young Spring\nWire (YGJ looks higher.\nThat many are switching from\nInternational Harvester (HR)\nto National Biscuit (BI).\nComeback Expected\nIn Business If Given\nChance, Expert Says\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nDirector New York University Dureitu\nof Bu.lnem Nraeorch and Former\nEconomist of Federal Trade\nCommla.lon\nIt seems that there is danger\nof becoming too impatient over\nthe slowness of business recovery.\nWhat is needed is (1) to note\nthe progress made in correcting\npast maladjustments, (2) to con\nfront frankly, but hopefully, the\nweak spots that still exist, and\n(3) to adjust our business policies\naccordingly.\nIt takes time to work out of a\nbusiness depression such as this\none. We always have and always\nwill do so. But sometimes a sick\nman makes himself worse by get\nting out of bed too soon. Just\nnow, the wisest course is keep\nquiet.\nIn our ordinary ills, nature\nworks the cure, and the best\nthing to do is to give her a\nchance. Just so, in the business\nworld, the forces which will in\ndue time bring recovery, are on\nthe job.\nOverproduction is being cor\nrected by curtailment of produc\ntion. Credit inflation is being\ncorrected by liquidation. Declin\ning commodity prices are gradu\nally correcting maleadjustments\nand slowing up production where\nit has been excessive.\nGradually, too, declining prices\nare bringing more and more\nthings within the limits of con\nsumer purchasing power\u2014though\nthis is a slow process.\nAlready the wholesale prices of\na good many basic commodities\nare down to very reasonable\nlevels. For example, we learn\nthat one of the biggest buyers\nof copper thinks the price of that\nDUNHILL CUTS\nDIVIDEND\nWhile State authorities are in\nvestigating the* pool manipula\ntions in Dunhill International,\nInc., stock directors of the com\npany have cut the annual divi\ndend rate to $1 from $4, paid\npreviously. A quarterly dividend\nof 2 cents a share has been de\nclared, payable October 15 to\nstockholders of record October 1.\nThe cortipany\u2019s earnings, made\npublic today, fell off sharply in\nthe first six months of this year,\ntotaling $68,657, or 47 cents a\nshare. This compares with $423,-\n417, or $2.38 a share, earned in\nthe first six months of 1929.\nOfficers and directors of the\ncompany are said to have had no\nconnection with the pool opera\ntions in the stock, which sold as\nhigh as $43.50 this year and $92\nlast year. Today it sold around i\nsl6. The low for the year is\n$15.50.\nDirectors of Park Tilford,\nInc., controlled by the same in\nterests as Dunhill, today omitted\nthe quarterly dividend due at this\ntime.\nFry Is Awarded\nRefund of Taxes\nA $51,843 income tax refund\nto Wilfred W. Fry, of Philadel\nphia, was announced by the In\nternal Revenue Bureau. Others\nwere to estates of:\nEdward J. Walsh, St. Louis,\n$52,705: Frank C, Snedaker, $45,-J\n636; George Edward Earnshaw,\n$36,524; Frank P, Clark, $37,686.\nall of Philadelphia: Frank Von\nTacky, Titusville, Pa., $49,672;\nHarriet V. S. Thorne, New York,\n$23,868; John F. La Boule, Mil\nwaukee, $20,703; Samuel Small,\nYork, Pa.. $27,451.\nTRAVEL BARGAINS BACK HOME b\nRAILROAD FARES CUT AROUT ONE HALF\nFROM WASHINGTON, D. C. I\nOCTOBER 4 th I\nFIRST CLASS ROUND TRIP FARES TO\nJacksonville, F1*529.00 Birmingham, A1a525.00 I\nMiami, Fl* 39.00 Montgomery, Ala 26.25\nWest Palm Beach, Fla. 38.00 Mobile, Ala 31.65 I\nSt. Petersburg, F1a.... 36.50 Atlanta, Ga-. 21.00 I\nTampa, Fl* 36.50 Athens, Ga 21.00\nSarasota, Fla 36.50 Columbus, Ga 23.00 I\nFt. Myers, Fla 36.50 Savannah, G* 24.00\nPensacola, Fla 31.65 Brunswick. Ga 26.00 I\nRaleigh, N. C 10.50 New Orleans, La 35.00 I\nNashville, Tenn 23.00 Camden, S. C 16.25 I\nChattanooga, Tenn. 21.00 Columbia, S. C. 17.45 I\nMemphis, Tenn 28.00 S. C. 17.70 I\nCorrespondingly low rates to many other points.\nReturn Limit October 24th. Certain Stopover Privileges En I\nRoute Tickets, Pullman Reservation* and Information\nI City Ticket Office, 714 14th St. N. W.\nTelephones, National 0637-0638.\nSEABOARD AIR LINE RAILWAY I\nTfce National Dally\nmetal low enough to warrant\nlarge purchases. Foreigners have\nbeen taking more cotton, and\nthe price of that material has\ncome\u2018down to a level at which\ntrade interests can buy to ad\nvantage on all further declines.\nWe now know that this is a\nworld-wide depression, affecting\nEurope, South America and the\nOrient. England, Argentina and\nJapan are hit as badly as we\nare. This situation has been\nmade more difficult by a bad\ndrought. No one could help these\nthings. Perhaps mistakes have\nbeen made in not realizing in\nadvance how bad the recession\n\u2022would be. Os course, errors were\nmade in the preceding boom\nperiod. The tariff hurts.\nBut that is water over the\ndam. Knocking will do ho good.\nWhat we need is intelligent pa\ntience, based on a frank facing\nof the facts. Above all I would\nput reasonable hopefulness. We\nshould recognize that progress is\nbeing made every day. We are\nsaving again, as the savings bank\nfigures show. That is a great\nrestorative.\nThe crisis is passed. We are\nstill sick. But we are going to\nget well. At the bottom of a\nbusiness depression, the next\nmove must be upward.\nBut we must avoid impatient\nand unwise efforts to get up too\nsoon. We should, for example,\nquit taking \u201ccredit hypodermics.\"\nWe have all the bank credit that\nis good for us. And our indus\ntrial leaders. should not try to\nexpand production too soon\u2014not\nuntil stocks of commodities are\nreduced, wholesale prices defi\nnitely stablized and retail prices\nadequately adjusted to wholesale\nmarkets.\nGRAND SEEKS\nCANADA CHAIN\nNegotiations are under way\nwhereby F. W. Grand Silver\nStores, Inc., will acquire the Can\nadian uhits of Metropolitan\nChain Stores, Inc. Conservations\nhave reached a point where an of\nficial statement can be looked for\nshortly. Transaction is likely to\nbe in the form of an outright pur\nchase.\nMetropolitan has 52 stores in\nCanada, operated by a subsidiary.\nMetropolitan Stores, Ltd.\nThe acquisition of Metropoli\ntan's Canadian properties will\nmean the initial entrance of\nGrand-Silver into Canada, its ac\ntivities having heretofore been\nconfined to the United States.\nIt will increase its chain to 203\nlocations and increase annual\nsales to around $40,000,000.\nF. W. Grand-Silver Stores,\nInc., is a holding company own\ning practically all of the common\nstocks of F. W. Grand 5-10-25\nCent Stores, Inc., and Isaac Silver\nBros. Co,, Inc. Through these\nsubsidiaries it operates 151 units\nwith an annual sales volume of\nabout $35,000,000.\nPub. Ser. of N. J. to\nSell Prd. Stock\nPublic Service Corp, of N. J\u201e\nin a campaign which will start\nOctober 1, will make a new offer\nof its 5 per cent cumulative stock,\nno-par value, the popular\nownership plan. The stock will\nbe sold at $97.50 a share and\naccrued dividends for cash or on\nterms of $lO down per share and\n$lO per share per month there\nafter until the final payment\nwhich will be $7.50 per share.\nPurchasers will receive interest\non installments as paid at the\nrate of 5 per cent per year.\nSATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 20. 1930\nPOWER TRAFFIC\nINTERSATE\nGROWING\nTrade Commission Reveals\n17.57 P. C. Was Sent Across\nState Lines During 1929\nThe legal foundation for Fed\neral regulation of power was\nstrengthened yesterday by a Fed\neral Trade Commission finding\nthat 17.57 per cent of all electric*\nenergy consumed last year moved\nacross State boundaries.\nAn interim report to the Sen\nate disclosed this large propor\ntion of Interstate commerce in\nvolved even after duplications\nwere eliminated. Including the\ncurrent crossing more than one\nState boundary, or crossing the\nsame boundary twice, the ratio\nof imports to electric energy con\nsumed was 19.65 per cent.\nPower Trust Differs\nThe power trust, fighting Fed\neral regulation and handling its\nfigures differently, has contended\nthe interstate movement is less\nthan 1 per cent.\nDisclosures of the vast inter\nchanges of energy are expected to\nbring a demand in December for\nimmediate Federal control over\nthe interstate movements and\nover holding companies.\nChairman Couzens, of the Sen\nate -Interstate Commerce Commit\ntee. has a Federal regulation bill\nof this sort pending. Couzens de\nlayed action last spring to leave\na clear road for reorganization of\nthe present Federal Power Com\nmission.\nThis reorganization has failed\nbecause the President appeared to\nlack power to make effective re\ncess appointments.\nLaunched Inquiry\nCouzens initiated the trade\ncommission\u2019s study of energy\nmovements, through a senate reso\nlution.\nNearly 16,000,000.000 kilowatt\nhours of energy crossed state and\ninternational boundaries in 1929,\nthe commission reported. This\ncompared with 94,703.000,000 kil\nowatt hours generated and 80,-\n955,000,000 kilowatt hours con\nsumed, after losses.\nHow much energy moves in and\nout of each state will be shown\nin a final report which is virtually\ncomplete and will be submitted to\nthe senate shortly.\nChemical Company\nChange Approved\nNEW YORK, Sept, 20. \u2014Reor\nganization plans of the American\nAgricultural Chemical Company\nfinally have been approved by the\ndirectors and will be submitted\nto stockholders, Horace Bowkar,\npresident, announced.\nPlan calls for the issuance, in\nexchange for stock of the Ameri\ncan Agricultural Chemical Com\npany, of Connecticut, of 317,875\nshares of no-par common of the\nAmerican Agricultural Chemical\nCompany, of Delaware.\n30 RAILWAY ENGINES\nTo finance the purchase of 30\nlocomotives, the Chicago Great\nWestern Railroad asked the Inter\nrtate Commerce Commission for\n'authority to issue $2,235,000 of\n4\u20192 per cent equipment trust cer\ntificates.\nAT YOUR THEATER JSZZt i\nOFFICIAL PROGRAMS of Theater members of the\nMotion Picture Theater Owners of District of Columbia\ns WARNER BNS. THfATEiS\n\u201cTHE SEA WOLF\u201d mmwmw\u2014\nStare: Fanchon A .Marco \"CHANGES\"\nAMBASSADOR 18 Vn?w?\u00b0\u2019 EARLE sS& et\n'W A R t N B r z B a a x k te X j o an tb \u00df bn nett\nPALACE\u2014 F St at 13th Ada,d Short SuMect\nf. \u2018GOOD NEWS? With Bessie Love An Al I A 4 H Street llrt\u00dfAE* 1830 0 Street\nCliff Edwards. Stage\u2014\u201c Happy ArULLU N. E. Rlnlt Northeast\nFfe landing,\u201d with Dave Schooler.\nV Hearst Metrotone News. Short JANET GAYNOR JACK HOLT end RALPH GRAVES\nE Subjects. Palace Orchestra in in \"HELL'S ISLAND\u201d\n\"SUNNY SIDE UP\u201d Vitaphone Variety\nW COLUMBIA\u2014 F St at 12th\nBS\u201c V? 4!: MALM METROPOLITAN I. ?SS\nSAP TOOM S*J*CTMr \u201cn\u2019nNOL.SH\"'\nC.inm.A.Orr.w.r. Comedy Added Shor. SuM.eW\nDtpilDl IP Phone North 7958\nk ue 6RAM s*\u00bb\u00aby\n-T WALTER HUSTON DIX I B LB B\nCTATE Bethesda. In T he BAD MAN\u201d In \"HAPPY DAYS\u201d\nVln I fa 'Vitaphone Variety Sportlight Reel Vitaphone Variety\nWestern Electric Sound System\nhi*\"! Keys to CENTRAL NI D h and F? Sts.* TIVOLI Northwest\nla ILIN COLN 1:l<i L Bt ERIC VON STROHEIM and WARNER BAXTER\nIlf biiidptte Colbert find Frederic CONSTANCE BENNfcTI !n\n\u2019Mawh In \u201cMANSLAUGHTER\u201d in \u201cTHREE FACES EAST\u201d \u201cROMANCE OF THE R' RANiy\nH B !9K?X o'wTlT COLOAt -\u25a0T.X.V.T.f' YORK \u25a0\u201c\u2019SUSS.\u201d*\nTin \"CALL OF THE FLESH\u201d GEOROE O\u2019BRIEN t JACK OAK I E\nM DASAI IA 8,8 F St- 8-W Comedy I Comedy\nA _2^ S ogG D g.WLES\u201d ERS T AK Q|| A h m r?nr\u201c\"\u2018 \u2018dT M-0 KEITHS T* W\nN DDAAnWAY ,th\u00dft w Talking Pictures at Their Best \"THE SPOILERS.\u201d with Gary Coopw.\nnil silT* Robt. Ames tn Doable Cross Roads\u2019 Alee\u2019 Kay Johnson and Betty CemptM\nSi in \u201cREDEMPTION\u201d Betty Compson In \u2019Midnight Mystery\" Usual Added Attractions\nTo Preside I\nI\nWl\nIm\nwk\n\u2014Hafrls-Ewing Photo\nW. FRANK PERSONS\nEXECUTIVE vice president of\nthe American Association of\nPersonal Finance Companies\nwho will preside at the round\ntable conference in the hall of\nthe U. S. Chamber of Com\nmerce September 23 to 26.\nRAIL BRANCH APPROVED\nThe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission authorized the Pitts\nburgh and Lake Erie to construct\na three and one-half mile branch\nfrom Monaca Borough to Potter\nTownship, Pa. The new line will\nserve a lead plant being con\nstructed near there.\nF 14th and H Sts. N. W.\nREDECORATED\nAnnounces the Fall Opening??\nTODAY\nEmory Daugherty Mr. Pep j and His Orchestra\nFeaturing I\nFloor Shows Direct from N. Y. I\nDaily Matinee\u2014Twice Nightly fl I\nElh\\ Dining\u2014Dancing\u2014Entertainment I\n\"Dance to Daugherty\"\n\u201cBACK HOME\u201d Excursion\nSATURDAY, OCTOBER 4th\nReduced Round Trip Fares From Washington\nNASHVILLE, TENN.. $23.00\nBIRMINGHAM, ALA $25.00\nMONTGOMERY, ALA.. $26.25\nMEMPHIS, TENN $28.00\nNEW ORLEANS, LA $35.00\nAlso Reduced Rates to Other Points\nFinal Return Limit October 24th\nFor fol! Information and ticket, apnly\nZdl\u00dfiS City Ticket Office. 714 14th St. N.\nor Union Station.\nIff MW CHESAPEAKE ONIO NY.\nJ. B. EDMUNDS, G. A.\nNational 0748-9\nfl. V. FLEMING\nTO WELCOME\nDELEGATES\nProminent D. C. People Plan\nning for Convention of Per\nsonal Finance Companies\nA group of Washingtonians,\nprominent in banking, social wel\nfare and religious circles, win\nextend a welcome in behalf of\nlocal institutions to the delegates\nto the sixteenth annual conven\ntion of the American Association\nof Personal Finance Companies,\nto be held at the Chamber of\nCommerce of 'the United States\nfrom September 23 to 26.\nRobert V. Fleming, president\nof the Riggs National Bank, one\nof the youngest chief executives\nof a major financial organization\nin the country, will deUver the\nprincipal address of welcome.\nChester Leasure, manager of the\ndepartment of referenda a 1 reso\nlutions of the Chamber r I n\nmerce of the United Stat' >ll\nact similarly in behalf of h<> lat\nter organization.\nThe invocation on the ig\nof the convention v, 11 be c ed\nby the Rev. jQr. John O\u2019Gn ac\nretary of the National Cot ce\nof Catholic Charities, and ;ly\nknown as an authority >-n bi\nology.. The Rev. Dr. J C.\nPalmer, pastor of the Was -ton\nHeights Presbyterian Ch.u: nil\ngive the invocation at the let\nto be held at the Mayflow< tel\nThursday evening.\n15","height":"30550","width":"23981"}}
